  "definitions": {
    "e-label": {
      "type": "elementHeading",
      "level": 6,
      "text": "CONCLUSIONS",
      "align": "left",
      "width": "hug",
      "height": "hug",
      "marginBottom": "0.5rem"
    },
    "e-synthesis": {
      "type": "elementRichText",
      "content": "### Synthesis\n\nPrint grids and responsive grids are not different tools solving the same problem — they are different theories of what layout is for. Print grids manage fixed spatial relationships. Responsive grids manage relationships under transformation.\n\nThe fluency that design education has historically cultivated — spatial intuition developed through fixed composition — is only a partial preparation for digital layout. The remaining fluency must be developed through working with constraints that change.",
      "level": 4,
      "align": "left",
      "width": "100%",
      "height": "hug",
      "wordWrap": true,
      "motionTiming": {
        "entrancePreset": "slideUp",
        "viewport": {
          "amount": 0.2
        },
        "entranceMotion": {
          "transition": {
            "duration": 0.45,
            "delay": 0
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "e-practice": {
      "type": "elementRichText",
      "content": "### In Practice\n\n**Start with content, not columns.** Grid decisions should follow from the nature of the content — its density, hierarchy, and reading rhythm — not from a default template.\n\n**Design at multiple breakpoints simultaneously.** A layout that solves elegantly at 1440px and fails at 375px has not solved a layout problem — it has only partially defined one.\n\n**Document your grid explicitly.** In collaborative environments, undocumented grid decisions are made again by everyone who inherits the work.\n\n**Violate the grid intentionally.** Breaking a grid is a formal decision. It requires knowing the grid well enough to understand what the break communicates.",
      "level": 4,
      "align": "left",
      "width": "100%",
      "height": "hug",
      "wordWrap": true,
      "motionTiming": {
        "entrancePreset": "slideUp",
        "viewport": {
          "amount": 0.2
        },
        "entranceMotion": {
          "transition": {
            "duration": 0.45,
            "delay": 0.08
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "e-reading": {
      "type": "elementRichText",
      "content": "### Further Reading\n\nMüller-Brockmann, J. — *Grid Systems in Graphic Design* (1981)\n\nSamara, T. — *Making and Breaking the Grid* (2002)\n\nKhoi Vinh — *Ordering Disorder* (2010)\n\nCSSWG — *CSS Grid Layout Module Level 1* (W3C, 2020)\n\nBringhurst, R. — *The Elements of Typographic Style* (1992)\n\nLupton, E. — *Thinking with Type* (2004)",
      "level": 5,
      "align": "left",
      "width": "100%",
      "height": "hug",
      "wordWrap": true,
      "motionTiming": {
        "entrancePreset": "fade",
        "viewport": {
          "amount": 0.2
        },
        "entranceMotion": {
          "transition": {
            "duration": 0.4,
            "delay": 0.16
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
